From: Logan Grasby <logan@smol.ai>
Date: Thu, 27 Feb 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] x86/apic: Skip LAPIC timer calibration on KVM guests

KVM emulates the LAPIC with a fixed bus frequency of 1 GHz (1ns per
cycle, set via APIC_BUS_CYCLE_NS_DEFAULT in the host KVM module). The
guest calibrate_APIC_clock() runs a ~200ms busy-wait loop to measure
this frequency, which is entirely unnecessary since the value is fixed
and known.

On AMD CPUs that lack X86_FEATURE_TSC_DEADLINE_TIMER (Zen 1/2/3), this
calibration cannot be skipped by any existing early-return path, adding
200ms+ to every VM boot.

When running under KVM, pre-compute lapic_timer_period from the known
1 GHz bus frequency. The existing early return via
lapic_init_clockevent() then fires, skipping the calibration loop while
keeping the LAPIC timer fully functional.

Tested on AMD Ryzen 5 3600 (Zen 2) with KVM:
  - Boot time: 351ms -> 147ms (~58% reduction)
  - Timer accuracy: no regression at any vCPU count (1/2/4)
  - Scheduler fairness: no regression
  - No kernel warnings

Signed-off-by: Logan Grasby <logan@smol.ai>
---
 arch/x86/kernel/apic/apic.c | 9 +++++++++
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+)

diff --git a/arch/x86/kernel/apic/apic.c b/arch/x86/kernel/apic/apic.c
index 373503838549..a1b2c3d4e5f6 100644
--- a/arch/x86/kernel/apic/apic.c
+++ b/arch/x86/kernel/apic/apic.c
@@ -61,6 +61,7 @@
 #include <asm/mce.h>
 #include <asm/tsc.h>
 #include <asm/hypervisor.h>
+#include <asm/kvm_para.h>
 #include <asm/cpu_device_id.h>
 #include <asm/intel-family.h>
 #include <asm/irq_regs.h>
@@ -798,6 +799,14 @@ static int __init calibrate_APIC_clock(void)
 	if (boot_cpu_has(X86_FEATURE_TSC_DEADLINE_TIMER))
 		return 0;

+	/*
+	 * KVM emulates the LAPIC with a fixed 1 GHz bus frequency
+	 * (APIC_BUS_CYCLE_NS_DEFAULT = 1). Pre-compute the timer period
+	 * (bus cycles per tick) to skip the ~200ms calibration busy-wait.
+	 */
+	if (kvm_para_available() && !lapic_timer_period)
+		lapic_timer_period = 1000000000UL / HZ;
+
 	/*
 	 * Check if lapic timer has already been calibrated by platform
 	 * specific routine, such as tsc calibration code. If so just fill
